rk of social, psychological, anthropological, and biological research on human development. By linking individual cases to broad social and cultural issues and illustrating the social toxicity and unresolved trauma that drive some people to kill, Dr. Garbarino highlights the humanity we share with killers and the role of understanding and empathy in breaking the cycle of violence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aEvidence, ExpertxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aMurderxPsychological aspectsxUnited States. 0aMurderersxPsychologyxUnited States. 0aTrials (Murder)xUnited States. 4aanthropological and biological research. 4aanthropologist. 4abiography. 4aemotional damage. 4aempathy for murderers. 4ahow does someone become a serial killer. 4amoral damage. 4amurderer interviews. 4apath of a killer. 4apsychological witness. 4apsychologist. 4apsychology. 4aserial killer pathology. 4aserial killers. 4asocial toxicity. 4atrauma. 4aunresolved trauma. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Forensic Psychology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311062111208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016z978311065748740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520958746423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520958746.jpg  a978-3-11-062111-2  UC Press eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-065748-7  UCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles